# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: golden-paths
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] A **best practice** is a method or technique that has been generally accepted as superior to alternatives because it tends to produce superior results.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Best practices are used to achieve quality as an alternative to mandatory standards.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Best practices can be based on self-assessment or benchmarking.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Best practice is a feature of accredited management standards such as ISO 9000 and ISO 14001.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Some consulting firms specialize in the area of best practice and offer ready-made templates to standardize business process documentation.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Sometimes a best practice is not applicable or is inappropriate for a particular organization's needs.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] A key strategic talent required when applying best practice to organizations is the ability to balance the unique qualities of an organization with the practices that it has in common with others.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Good operating practice is a strategic management term.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] More specific uses of the term include good agricultural practices, good manufacturing practice, good laboratory practice, good clinical practice, and good distribution practice.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Best practice is a form of program evaluation in public policy.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] It is the process of reviewing policy alternatives that have been effective in addressing similar issues in the past and could be applied to a current problem.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Determining best practices to address a particular policy problem is a commonly used but little understood tool of analysis because the concept is vague and should therefore be examined with caution.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Vagueness stems from the term "best" which is subjective.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] While some research and evidence must go into determining a practice the "best" it is more helpful to simply determine if a practice has worked exceptionally well and why.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Instead of it being "the best", a practice might simply be a smart practice, a good practice, or a promising practice.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] This allows for a mix and match approach for making recommendations that might encompass pieces of many good practices.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Excessive optimism about the expected impact of untested smart practices is a common critique.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] If a current practice is known to be ineffective, implementing a promising alternative after weighing the alternatives may be worth the risk.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Bretschneider et al. offers an alternate methodology for Best Practices research in 2005.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Bretschneider's approach is much more technical than Bardach's, and explores issues of completeness and comparability.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] He addresses the fact that fully establishing whether a practice is truly a best practice would require assessment in all contexts, while in practice, only example cases are analyzed.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Bretschneider also stresses the fact that in order for something to be considered a "best practice" it must be arrived at through a comparative process between methodologies.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] There are many examples of the use of best/smart practice evaluations in Public Policy.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) produces a document called The Clean Energy-Environment Guide to Action, designed to share practices found to be successful and best by states, to determine what is most suitable for them to use in generating clean energy policies and programs.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] The guide includes 16 clean energy policies and programs that offer opportunities for states to save energy, improve air quality, lower greenhouse gas emission and increase economic development.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] An example of a successful best practice from the guide is building codes for energy efficiency.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] This practice is to use building energy codes to set requirements that establish a minimum level of energy efficiency standards for residential and commercial buildings.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] California Energy Code Title 24 is one "best practice" that is highlighted in this guide.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] The following points for energy code implementation is to educate and train key audiences, supply the right resources, and to provide budget and staff for the program.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Eugene Bardach has a list of smart practice candidates in his book *A Practical Guide for Policy Analysis*, Eightfold Path (policy analysis).
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] One example is the tutoring program for children in grades 1-3 called Reading One-to-One.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] The program from Texas includes one on one tutoring with supervision and simple structured instruction in phonemic awareness.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Phonemic awareness is one highly regarded predictor of how well a child will learn to read in the first two years of school.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] The program takes advantage of the fact that many children, especially ESL students, fail in reading because it is very hard for second language students to understand and pronounce sounds in English.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] The program is easily duplicated at a relatively low cost because of the straight forward teaching materials, systematic methods and administrative oversight.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] In September 2013 at the New York State Conference for Mayors and Municipal Officials, successes, ideas and information on best practices were shared among government peers.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] A best practice that was highlighted at the conference was how Salinas, California is rebuilding their economy by engaging technology companies with their agricultural business in order to grow jobs.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Salinas is taking advantage of an idle opportunity.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] The area already has abundant lettuce fields and now the city is marketing itself as a lab for agricultural technology.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] This public/private partnership includes a new nonprofit called the Steinbeck Innovation Foundation to increase investment in new technologies to help the area's agricultural industry.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] In recent years, public agencies and non-governmental organizations have been exploring and adopting best practices when delivering health and human services.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] In these settings, the use of the terms "promising practices", "best practices", and "evidence-based practices" is common and often confusing as there is not a general consensus on what constitutes promising practices or best practices.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] In this context, the use of the terms "best practices" and "evidence-based practices" are often used interchangeably.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Evidence-based practices are methods or techniques that have documented outcomes and ability to replicate as key factors.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Despite these challenges, the literature suggests that there is some common use of and criteria for identifying best practices.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] For example, a general working definition used by the U.S.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Since evidence of effectiveness, the potential for taking the intervention to scale and generalizing the results to other populations and settings are key factors for best practices, the manner in which a method or intervention becomes a best practice can take some time and effort.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] The table below demonstrates the process for a promising practice to achieve the status of research-validated best practice.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] The National Registry of Evidence-Based Programs and Practices (NREPP) is a searchable online registry of interventions supporting substance abuse prevention and mental health treatment that has been reviewed and rated by independent reviewers.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] NREPP accepts submissions for interventions that meet minimum requirements to be considered for review.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] NREPP is not an exhaustive list of interventions and inclusion in the registry does not constitute an endorsement.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] There is existing controversy about the lack of culturally appropriate evidence-based best practices and the need to utilize a research-based approach to validate interventions.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Some communities have deployed practices over a long period of time that has produced positive outcomes as well as a general community consensus to be successful.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] The California Reducing Disparities Project (CRDP) is working to identify such practices.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] CRDP intends to improve access, quality of care, and increase positive outcomes for racial, ethnic and cultural communities.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] These communities have been identified as (1) African American, (2) Asian/Pacific Islanders, (3) Latinos, (4) lesbian, gay, bi-sexual, transgender, questioning, and (5) Native Americans.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Strategic Planning Workgroups composed of mental health providers and community members as well as consumers and family members are given the task of identifying new approaches toward reducing disparities.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] The five Strategic Planning Workgroups work to identify new service delivery approaches defined by multicultural communities for multicultural communities using community-defined evidence to improve outcomes and reduce disparities.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Financing Clean Air Programs, and example taken from NGA This is a quick guide put together by the NGA Center for Best Practices.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] It explores what clean air programs currently exist and how they are being financed.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Rather than stating one best practice to tackling clean air, this report creates a table of the different programs, how they are being financed, and in what state.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Governors and their staffs can then look for characteristics and solutions that are most realistic and applicable to their situation.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] The key is to tailor current practices that are in the world to the specific situation you are looking to solve.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Best practices are meant to give insight into existing strategies.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] The concept of best practice has been employed extensively in environmental management.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] STEM Program explanation is taken from Angela Baber's report to the NGA.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] The NGA has identified science, technology, engineering, and mathematics (STEM) as important skills that need to be developed in community colleges in order to create a strong workforce.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Many states are creating or have created STEM Programs to address this issue.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Preventive Services Task Force (USPSTF) makes evidence-based recommendations on clinical preventive services.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] The Task Force recommendations are based on systematic reviews and assessment of the available medical evidence.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] The San Francisco Public Health Department conducted The Transgender Best Practices Guide project, a best practices document for cultural and service competency in working with transgender clients within HIV/AIDS service- provision settings.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Following an intensive literature search and consumer focus group, a Working Group composed of noted community leaders; activists, professionals, and transgender consumers participated in the development of the Best Practices guide.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Topics covered by the Best Practices guide include mental health issues; gender identity; hormone use and clinical care practices.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] The Best Practices guide is currently in production; it will be published and distributed to EMA providers, as well as to select organizations nationwide.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] In addition, four large-scale EMA provider training will be provided to educate providers on the Best Practices recommendations and standard measures.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] This is the first national federally funded effort to develop a Best Practices guide for providers who serve the HIV positive transgender community.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] The nonprofit/voluntary sector is generally lacking tools for sharing and accessing best practices.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Steps are being taken in some parts of the world, for example in the European Union, where the Europe 2020 Strategy has as a top priority the exchange of good practices and networking (including the nonprofit sector).
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] An initiative of sharing good practices in terms of human resources (HR) and leadership among European nonprofit organizations was financed by the EU and launched in 2013, called HR Twinning.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] The platform allows the public to search for good practices and its members the possibility to share their practices, engage in discussions in the forum section and enroll their organization.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] The project is currently limited to a European audience.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Nearly every industry and professional discipline discusses best practices.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Areas of note include information technology development (such as new software), construction, transportation, business management, sustainable development and various aspects of project management.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Best practices also occur in healthcare to deliver high-quality care that promotes best outcomes.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Best practices are used within business areas including sales, manufacturing, teaching, computer programming, road construction, health care, insurance, telecommunication and public policy.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] There are some criticisms of the term "best practice".
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Eugene Bardach claims that the work necessary to deem a practice the "best" is rarely done.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Most of the time, one will find "good" practices or "smart" practices that offer insight into solutions that may or may not work for a given situation.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Quinn proposes avoiding asking or entertaining the question "Which is best?" and says that more nuanced questions related to conditions and contexts should be asked instead.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] He further suggests terms which "tend less toward overgeneralization" like *better practices, effective practices,* or *promising practices*.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Eric Darling states it is not best practice it's common practice.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Specifically relating to the field of projects based work Dr Darling asserts in the past work practices were pragmatic in order to get achieve the task, recent decades has seen rise in opinions with limited evidence of best.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Further rather than best practice perhaps we should strive for evidence based practice.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Scott Ambler challenges the assumptions that there can be a recommended practice that is best in all cases.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Instead, he offers an alternative view, "contextual practice", in which the notion of what is "best" will vary with the context.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] Similarly, Cem Kaner and James Bach provide two scenarios to illustrate the contextual nature of "best practice" in their article.
[src:golden-paths/best-practice] In essence, such critiques are consistent with the contingency theory, which was developed during the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:golden-paths/devops] Although debated, DevOps is generally characterized by three key principles: shared ownership, workflow automation, and rapid feedback.
[src:golden-paths/devops] However, the term is used in multiple contexts.
[src:golden-paths/devops] At its most successful, DevOps is a combination of specific practices, culture change, and tools.
[src:golden-paths/devops] Proposals to combine software development methodologies with deployment and operations concepts first appeared in the late 80s and early 90s.
[src:golden-paths/devops] In 2009, the first DevOps Days conference was held in Ghent, Belgium.
[src:golden-paths/devops] The conference was founded by Belgian IT consultant and practitioner Patrick Debois.
[src:golden-paths/devops] The conference has now spread to other countries.
[src:golden-paths/devops] In 2012, the first "State of DevOps" report was published by Alanna Brown at Puppet Labs.
[src:golden-paths/devops] In 2016, the DORA metrics for throughput (deployment frequency, lead time for changes), and stability (mean time to recover, change failure rate) were published in that year's State of DevOps report.
[src:golden-paths/devops] However, the research methodology and metrics were criticized by some experts.
[src:golden-paths/devops] In response to these criticisms, the 2023 State of DevOps report published changes that updated the stability metric "mean time to recover" to "failed deployment recovery time" acknowledging the confusion the previous metric had caused.
[src:golden-paths/devops] The 2024 report restructured the metrics framework by moving failed deployment recovery time from stability to throughput and introducing a new "rework rate" metric measuring the proportion of unplanned deployments made to fix user-visible issues.
[src:golden-paths/devops] In 2025, DORA moved away from sorting teams into performance tiers and instead introduced seven team archetypes that combine delivery metrics with human factors like burnout, friction, and perceived value.
[src:golden-paths/devops] DevOps Research and Assessment (DORA) has developed a set of metrics which are intended to measure software development efficiency and reliability.
[src:golden-paths/devops] Many of the ideas fundamental to DevOps are similar to other well-known practices, such as Lean and Deming's Plan-Do-Check-Act cycle, The Toyota Way, and the Agile approach of breaking down components and batch sizes.
[src:golden-paths/devops] Contrary to the "top-down" prescriptive approach and rigid framework of ITIL in the 1990s, DevOps is "bottom-up" and flexible, having been created by software engineers for their own needs.
[src:golden-paths/devops] The motivations for what has become modern DevOps and several standard DevOps practices such as automated build and test, continuous integration, and continuous delivery originated in the Agile world, which informally dates to the 1990s and formally to 2001.
[src:golden-paths/devops] Agile development teams using methods such as extreme programming couldn't "satisfy the customer through early and continuous delivery of valuable software" unless they took responsibility for operations and infrastructure for their applications, automating much of that work.
[src:golden-paths/devops] Because Scrum emerged as the dominant Agile framework in the early 2000s and it omitted the engineering practices that were part of many Agile teams, the momentum to automate operations and infrastructure functions splintered from Agile and expanded into what has become modern DevOps.
[src:golden-paths/devops] Today, DevOps focuses on deploying methodology-agnostic, developed software.
[src:golden-paths/devops] ArchOps starts from software architecture artifacts instead of source code for operational deployment, as opposed to DevOps.
[src:golden-paths/devops] ArchOps holds that architectural models are first-class entities in software development, deployment, and operations.
[src:golden-paths/devops] CI/CD is as critical to DevOps success as automation.
[src:golden-paths/devops] Additionally, improved collaboration and communication between and within teams helps them achieve faster time to market with reduced risks.
[src:golden-paths/devops] Database DevOps applies DevOps and CI/CD principles directly to database development and operations.
[src:golden-paths/devops] Integrating schema changes, migrations, reference data, and other data-layer updates into the same version-controlled and automated pipelines used for application code enables more reliable deployments.
[src:golden-paths/devops] This approach also enables improved coordination between application and data changes.
[src:golden-paths/devops] Typical database DevOps practices include placing database schema definitions under version control, applying automated tests (such as unit tests or migration validation) to database changes, and deploying those changes through CI/CD pipelines.
[src:golden-paths/devops] These practices reduce what is commonly referred to as "schema drift" between development and production systems and lower the risk of deployment failures.
[src:golden-paths/devops] Mobile DevOps is a methodology that applies DevOps' principles to the development of mobile applications.
[src:golden-paths/devops] Traditional DevOps focuses on streamlining the general software development process, but mobile development has unique challenges that require a tailored approach.
[src:golden-paths/devops] Mobile DevOps is not simply a branch of DevOps specific to mobile app development, but rather an extension and reinterpretation of the DevOps philosophy tailored to mobile's specific requirements.
[src:golden-paths/devops] In 2003, Google developed site reliability engineering (SRE), an approach for releasing new features continuously into large-scale, high-availability systems while maintaining a high-quality end-user experience.
[src:golden-paths/devops] While SRE predates the development of DevOps, they are generally viewed as being related to each other.
[src:golden-paths/devops] Some of the original authors of the discipline consider SRE as an implementation of DevOps.
[src:golden-paths/devops] The Toyota Production System (TPS), inspired lean thinking with its focus on continuous improvement, kaizen, flow, and small batches.
[src:golden-paths/devops] The andon cord principle of creating fast feedback, swarming, and solving problems stems from TPS.
[src:golden-paths/devops] As its name implies, DevSecOps integrates DevOps within security practices.
[src:golden-paths/devops] Contrary to a traditional centralized security team model, each delivery team is empowered to factor the correct security controls into their software delivery.
[src:golden-paths/devops] Teams perform tests and implement security practices earlier in the development lifecycle, hence the term "shift left".
[src:golden-paths/devops] Security is tested in three main areas: static, software composition, and dynamic.
[src:golden-paths/devops] Checking software statically via static application security testing (SAST) is white-box testing with special focus on security.
[src:golden-paths/devops] Depending on the programming language, different tools are needed to do such static code analysis.
[src:golden-paths/devops] The software composition is analyzed, especially libraries, and the version of each component is checked against vulnerability lists published by CERT and other expert groups.
[src:golden-paths/devops] When giving software to clients, library licenses and their match to the license of the software distributed are in focus, especially copyleft licenses.
[src:golden-paths/devops] In dynamic testing, also called black-box testing, software is tested without knowing its inner functions.
[src:golden-paths/devops] In DevSecOps this practice may be referred to as dynamic application security testing (DAST) or penetration testing.
[src:golden-paths/devops] The goal is early detection of defects including cross-site scripting and SQL injection vulnerabilities.
[src:golden-paths/devops] Often, detected defects from static and dynamic testing are triaged and categorized under taxonomies like the Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE), maintained by the Mitre Corporation.
[src:golden-paths/devops] This facilitates the prioritization of security bug fixes and also allows frequently recurring weaknesses to be fixed with recommended mitigations.
[src:golden-paths/devops] As of 2025, CWE maintained its own list of frequently-occurring weaknesses, the CWE Top 25.
[src:golden-paths/devops] In addition, organizations like Open Worldwide Application Security Project (OWASP) maintain lists of industry-wide frequently recurring software weaknesses.
[src:golden-paths/devops] DevSecOps has also been described as a cultural shift involving a holistic approach to producing secure software by integrating security education, security by design, and security automation.
[src:golden-paths/devops] DevOps initiatives can change how a company's operations, developers, and testers collaborate during development and delivery processes.
[src:golden-paths/devops] DevOps attempts to support consistency, reliability, and efficiency within an organization.
[src:golden-paths/devops] This is usually enabled by a shared code repository or version control.
[src:golden-paths/devops] Many organizations use version control to facilitate DevOps automation technologies like virtual machines, containerization (or OS-level virtualization), and CI/CD, with the Git version control system and the GitHub platform referenced as examples.
[src:golden-paths/devops] It takes its name from the popular version control system Git, and the specific state of deployment configuration is also version-controlled.
[src:golden-paths/devops] Configuration changes can be managed using code review practices, and can be rolled back using version-controlling.
[src:golden-paths/devops] Essentially, all of the changes to a code are tracked, bookmarked, and making any updates to the history can be made easier.
[src:golden-paths/devops] DataOps incorporates the Agile methodology to shorten the cycle time of analytics development in alignment with business goals.
[src:golden-paths/devops] DevOps focuses on continuous delivery by leveraging on-demand IT resources and by automating test and deployment of software.
[src:golden-paths/devops] This merging of software *development* and IT *operations* has improved velocity, quality, predictability and scale of software engineering and deployment.
[src:golden-paths/devops] Borrowing methods from DevOps, DataOps seeks to bring these same improvements to data analytics.
[src:golden-paths/devops] DataOps utilizes statistical process control (SPC) to monitor and control the data analytics pipeline.
[src:golden-paths/devops] With SPC in place, the data flowing through an operational system is constantly monitored and verified.
[src:golden-paths/devops] If an anomaly occurs, the data analytics team can be notified with an automated alert.
[src:golden-paths/devops] DataOps is not tied to a particular technology, architecture, tool, language or framework.
[src:golden-paths/devops] The best DataOps tools promote collaboration, orchestration, quality, security, access and ease of use.
[src:golden-paths/devops] DataOps was first introduced by InformationWeek contributing editor Lenny Liebmann in a blog post on the IBM Big Data & Analytics Hub titled "3 reasons why DataOps is essential for big data success" on June 19, 2014.
[src:golden-paths/devops] The term DataOps was later popularized by Andy Palmer of Tamr and Steph Locke.
[src:golden-paths/devops] DataOps is a moniker for "Data Operations." 2017 was a significant year for DataOps, with significant ecosystem development, analyst coverage, increased keyword searches, surveys, publications, and open source projects.
[src:golden-paths/devops] Gartner placed DataOps on the Hype Cycle for Data Management in 2018.
[src:golden-paths/devops] The total world data volume is forecast to grow at a rate of 32% CAGR to 180 Zettabytes by 2025 (Source: IDC).
[src:golden-paths/devops] DataOps seeks to provide the tools, processes, and organizational structures to accommodate this significant increase in data.
[src:golden-paths/devops] Automation streamlines data preboarding, ingestion, and the management of large integrated databases, freeing the data team to develop new analytics in a more efficient and effective way.
[src:golden-paths/devops] DataOps seeks to increase velocity, reliability, and quality of data analytics.
[src:golden-paths/devops] It emphasizes communication, collaboration, integration, automation, measurement and cooperation between data scientists, analysts, data/ETL (extract, transform, load) engineers, information technology (IT), and quality assurance/governance.
[src:golden-paths/reference-architecture] A **reference architecture** in the field of software architecture or enterprise architecture provides a template solution for an architecture for a particular domain.
[src:golden-paths/reference-architecture] It also provides a common vocabulary with which to discuss implementations, often with the aim to stress commonality.
[src:golden-paths/reference-architecture] A **software reference architecture** is a software architecture where the structures and respective elements and relations provide templates for concrete architectures in a particular domain or in a family of software systems.
[src:golden-paths/reference-architecture] An implementation of a reference architecture is called a framework or an application platform.
[src:golden-paths/reference-architecture] A reference architecture often consists of a list of functions and some indication of their interfaces (or APIs) and interactions with each other and with functions located outside of the scope of the reference architecture.
[src:golden-paths/reference-architecture] Reference architectures can be defined at different levels of abstraction.
[src:golden-paths/reference-architecture] A highly abstract one might show different pieces of equipment on a communications network, each providing different functions.
[src:golden-paths/reference-architecture] A lower level one might demonstrate the interactions of procedures (or methods) within a computer program defined to perform a very specific task.
[src:golden-paths/reference-architecture] A reference architecture provides a template, often based on the generalization of a set of solutions.
[src:golden-paths/reference-architecture] These solutions may have been generalized and structured for the depiction of one or more architecture structures based on the harvesting of a set of patterns that have been observed in a number of successful implementations.
[src:golden-paths/reference-architecture] Further it shows how to compose these parts together into a solution.
[src:golden-paths/reference-architecture] Reference Architectures will be instantiated for a particular domain or for specific projects.
[src:golden-paths/reference-architecture] Adopting a reference architecture within an organization accelerates delivery through the re-use of an effective solution and provides a basis for governance to ensure the consistency and applicability of technology use within an organization.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] A **software development process** prescribes a process for developing software.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] It typically divides an overall effort into smaller steps or sub-processes that are intended to ensure high-quality results.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] The process may describe specific deliverables – artifacts to be created and completed.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Although not strictly limited to it, software development process often refers to the high-level process that governs the development of a software system from its beginning to its end of life – known as a methodology, model or framework.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] The system development life cycle (SDLC) describes the typical phases that a development effort goes through from the beginning to the end of life for a system – including a software system.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] A methodology prescribes how engineers go about their work in order to move the system through its life cycle.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] A methodology is a classification of processes or a blueprint for a process that is devised for the SDLC.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] For example, many processes can be classified as a spiral model.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Software process and software quality are closely interrelated; some unexpected facets and effects have been observed in practice.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] The SDLC drives the definition of a methodology in that a methodology must address the phases of the SDLC.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Generally, a methodology is designed to result in a high-quality system that meets or exceeds expectations (requirements) and is delivered on time and within budget even though computer systems can be complex and integrate disparate components.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Various methodologies have been devised, including waterfall, spiral, agile, rapid prototyping, incremental, and synchronize and stabilize.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] A major difference between methodologies is the degree to which the phases are sequential vs. iterative.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Agile methodologies, such as XP and scrum, focus on lightweight processes that allow for rapid changes.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Iterative methodologies, such as Rational Unified Process and dynamic systems development method, focus on stabilizing project scope and iteratively expanding or improving products.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Sequential or big-design-up-front (BDUF) models, such as waterfall, focus on complete and correct planning to guide larger projects and limit risks to successful and predictable results.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Anamorphic development is guided by project scope and adaptive iterations.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] In scrum, for example, one could say a single user story goes through all the phases of the SDLC within a two-week sprint.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] By contrast the waterfall methodology, where every business requirement is translated into feature/functional descriptions which are then all implemented typically over a period of months or longer.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] A project can include both a project life cycle (PLC) and an SDLC, which describe different activities.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] According to Taylor (2004), "the project life cycle encompasses all the activities of the project, while the systems development life cycle focuses on realizing the product requirements".
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] The term *SDLC* is often used as an abbreviated version of *SDLC methodology*.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Further, some use *SDLC* and *traditional SDLC* to mean the waterfall methodology.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] According to Elliott (2004), SDLC "originated in the 1960s, to develop large scale functional business systems in an age of large scale business conglomerates.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Information systems activities revolved around heavy data processing and number crunching routines".
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] The structured systems analysis and design method (SSADM) was produced for the UK government Office of Government Commerce in the 1980s.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Ever since, according to Elliott (2004), "the traditional life cycle approaches to systems development have been increasingly replaced with alternative approaches and frameworks, which attempted to overcome some of the inherent deficiencies of the traditional SDLC".
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Since DSDM in 1994, all of the methodologies on the above list except RUP have been agile methodologies - yet many organizations, especially governments, still use pre-agile processes (often waterfall or similar).
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] The following are notable methodologies somewhat ordered by popularity.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Agile software development refers to a group of frameworks based on iterative development, where requirements and solutions evolve via collaboration between self-organizing cross-functional teams.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] The term was coined in the year 2001 when the Agile Manifesto was formulated.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] The waterfall model is a sequential development approach, in which development flows one way (like a waterfall) through the SDLC phases.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] In 1988, Barry Boehm published a software system development spiral model, which combines key aspects of the waterfall model and rapid prototyping, in an effort to combine advantages of top-down and bottom-up concepts.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] It emphases a key area many felt had been neglected by other methodologies: deliberate iterative risk analysis, particularly suited to large-scale complex systems.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Various methods combine linear and iterative methodologies, with the primary objective of reducing inherent project risk by breaking a project into smaller segments and providing more ease-of-change during the development process.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Software prototyping is about creating prototypes, i.e. incomplete versions of the software program being developed.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Rapid application development (RAD) is a methodology which favors iterative development and the rapid construction of prototypes instead of large amounts of up-front planning.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] The "planning" of software developed using RAD is interleaved with writing the software itself.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] The lack of extensive pre-planning generally allows software to be written much faster and makes it easier to change requirements.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Shape Up is a software development approach introduced by Basecamp in 2018.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] It is a set of principles and techniques that Basecamp developed internally to overcome the problem of projects dragging on with no clear end.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Its primary target audience is remote teams.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Shape Up has no estimation and velocity tracking, backlogs, or sprints, unlike waterfall, agile, or scrum.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Instead, those concepts are replaced with appetite, betting, and cycles.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] As of 2022, besides Basecamp, notable organizations that have adopted Shape Up include UserVoice and Block.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Chaos model has one main rule: always resolve the most important issue first.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Incremental funding methodology - an iterative approach.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Lightweight methodology - a general term for methods that only have a few rules and practices.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Structured systems analysis and design method - a specific version of waterfall.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] As part of the larger slow movement, emphasizes careful and gradual work without (or minimal) time pressures.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Slow programming aims to avoid bugs and overly quick release schedules.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] V-Model (software development) - an extension of the waterfall model.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Unified Process (UP) is an iterative software development methodology framework, based on Unified Modeling Language (UML).
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] UP organizes the development of software into four phases, each consisting of one or more executable iterations of the software at that stage of development: inception, elaboration, construction, and guidelines.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] The waterfall model describes the SDLC phases such that each builds on the result of the previous one.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Not every project requires that the phases be sequential.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] For relatively simple projects, phases may be combined or overlapping.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Alternative methodologies to waterfall are described and compared below.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Some process models are abstract descriptions for evaluating, comparing, and improving the specific process adopted by an organization.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] ISO/IEC 12207 is the international standard describing the method to select, implement, and monitor the life cycle for software.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] The Capability Maturity Model Integration (CMMI) is one of the leading models and is based on best practices.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Independent assessments grade organizations on how well they follow their defined processes, not on the quality of those processes or the software produced.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] ISO 9000 describes standards for a formally organized process to manufacture a product and the methods of managing and monitoring progress.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Although the standard was originally created for the manufacturing sector, ISO 9000 standards have been applied to software development as well.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Like CMMI, certification with ISO 9000 does not guarantee the quality of the end result, only that formalized business processes have been followed.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] ISO/IEC 15504 *Information technology—Process assessment*, a.k.a.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Software Process Improvement Capability Determination (SPICE), is a framework for the assessment of software processes.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] This standard is aimed at setting out a clear model for process comparison.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] It models processes to manage, control, guide, and monitor software development.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] This model is then used to measure what a development organization or project team actually does during software development.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] This information is analyzed to identify weaknesses and drive improvement.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] It also identifies strengths that can be continued or integrated into common practice for that organization or team.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] ISO/IEC 24744 *Software Engineering—Metamodel for Development Methodologies*, is a power type-based metamodel for software development methodologies.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Soft systems methodology is a general method for improving management processes.
[src:golden-paths/software-development-process] Method engineering is a general method for improving information system processes.
[src:golden-paths/software-templates] The Software Templates part of Backstage is a tool that can help you create Components inside Backstage.
[src:golden-paths/software-templates] By default, it has the ability to load skeletons of code, template in some variables, and then publish the template to some locations like GitHub or GitLab.
[src:golden-paths/software-templates] When creating custom scaffolder actions, **use camelCase for action IDs** instead of kebab-case.
[src:golden-paths/software-templates] Action IDs with dashes (like `fetch-component-id`) will cause template expressions like `${{ steps.fetch-component-id.output.componentId }}` to return `NaN` because the dashes are evaluated as subtraction operators in JavaScript expressions.
[src:golden-paths/software-templates] See the Writing Custom Actions guide for more details.
[src:golden-paths/software-templates] These docs assume you have already gone over the Backstage Getting Started section and you are able to run Backstage locally or it has been deployed somewhere.
[src:golden-paths/software-templates] Software Templates you have imported into Backstage can be found under `/create`.
[src:golden-paths/software-templates] If you're running Backstage locally, this will be `http://localhost:3000/create`.
[src:golden-paths/software-templates] When you select a template that you want to create, you'll be taken to the next page which may or may not look different for each template.
[src:golden-paths/software-templates] Each template can ask for different input variables, and they are then passed to the templater internally.
[src:golden-paths/software-templates] Templates generally consist of a set of steps, and each step can have its own set of required or optional inputs, as you can see in the image below we are now prompted to input some GitHub repository information.
[src:golden-paths/software-templates] Before you run the template, you'll be taken to a summary page where you can verify the inputs you have provided before we run the template.
[src:golden-paths/software-templates] This is a good time to double check that you have provided the correct information and allows you to go back and change any of the inputs if you need to.
[src:golden-paths/software-templates] Once you are happy with the inputs you have provided, you can click on the `Create` button to run the template.
[src:golden-paths/software-templates] Once the template has finished running, you'll be taken to a success page where you can see the results of the template.
[src:golden-paths/software-templates] If it fails, you'll be able to click on each section to get the log from the step that failed which can be helpful in debugging.
[src:golden-paths/software-templates] You can also cancel the running process.
[src:golden-paths/software-templates] Once you clicked on button "Cancel", the abort signal will be sent to a task and all next steps won't be executed.
[src:golden-paths/software-templates] The current step will be cancelled only if it supports it.
[src:golden-paths/software-templates] Once the template has finished running, and from the screenshot above, when its successful, you are presented with two links, clicking on them will take you to the templated repository we created!
[src:golden-paths/software-templates] There could be situations where you would like to disable the `Register Existing Component` button for your users.
[src:golden-paths/software-templates] After the change, you should no longer see the button.
[src:golden-paths/software-templates] Each execution of a template is treated as a unique task, identifiable by its own unique ID.
[src:golden-paths/software-templates] To view a list of previously executed template tasks, navigate to the "Create" page and access the "Task List" from the context menu (represented by the vertical ellipsis, or 'kebab menu', icon in the upper right corner).
[src:golden-paths/software-templates] If you wish to re-run a previously executed template, navigate to the template tasks page.
[src:golden-paths/software-templates] Locate the desired task and select the "Start Over" option from the context menu.
[src:golden-paths/software-templates] This action will initiate a new execution of the selected template, pre-populated with the same parameters as the previous run, but these parameters can be edited before re-execution.
[src:golden-paths/software-templates] In the event of a failed template execution, the "Start Over" option can be used to re-execute the template.
[src:golden-paths/software-templates] The parameters from the original run will be pre-filled, but they can be adjusted as needed before retrying the template.
[src:golden-paths/software-templates] The Backstage Demo Site has a template you are able to run, which is where the screenshots in this document were taken from!
[src:golden-paths/standardization] In social sciences, including economics, the idea of *standardization* is close to the solution for a coordination problem, a situation in which all parties can realize mutual gains, but only by making mutually consistent decisions.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Divergent national standards impose costs on consumers and can be a form of non-tariff trade barrier.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Standard weights and measures were developed by the Indus Valley civilization.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] The centralized weight and measure system served the commercial interest of Indus merchants as smaller weight measures were used to measure luxury goods while larger weights were employed for buying bulkier items, such as food grains etc.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Weights existed in multiples of a standard weight and in categories.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Technical standardization enabled gauging devices to be effectively used in angular measurement and measurement for construction.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Uniform units of length were used in the planning of towns such as Lothal, Surkotada, Kalibangan, Dolavira, Harappa, and Mohenjo-daro.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] The weights and measures of the Indus civilization also reached Persia and Central Asia, where they were further modified.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] The implementation of standards in industry and commerce became highly important with the onset of the Industrial Revolution and the need for high-precision machine tools and interchangeable parts.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Henry Maudslay developed the first industrially practical screw-cutting lathe in 1800.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] This allowed for the standardization of screw thread sizes for the first time and paved the way for the practical application of interchangeability (an idea that was already taking hold) to nuts and bolts.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Before this, screw threads were usually made by chipping and filing (that is, with skilled freehand use of chisels and files).
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Nuts were rare; metal screws, when made at all, were usually for use in wood.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Metal bolts passing through wood framing to a metal fastening on the other side were usually fastened in non-threaded ways (such as clinching or upsetting against a washer).
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Maudslay standardized the screw threads used in his workshop and produced sets of taps and dies that would make nuts and bolts consistently to those standards, so that any bolt of the appropriate size would fit any nut of the same size.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] This was a major advance in workshop technology.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Maudslay's work, as well as the contributions of other engineers, accomplished a modest amount of industry standardization; some companies' in-house standards spread a bit within their industries.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Joseph Whitworth's screw thread measurements were adopted as the first (unofficial) national standard by companies around the country in 1841.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] It came to be known as the British Standard Whitworth, and was widely adopted in other countries.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] This new standard specified a 55° thread angle and a thread depth of 0.640327*p* and a radius of 0.137329*p*, where *p* is the pitch.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] The thread pitch increased with diameter in steps specified on a chart.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] An example of the use of the Whitworth thread is the Royal Navy's Crimean War gunboats.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] These were the first instance of "mass-production" techniques being applied to marine engineering.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] With the adoption of BSW by British railway lines, many of which had previously used their own standard both for threads and for bolt head and nut profiles, and improving manufacturing techniques, it came to dominate British manufacturing.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] American Unified Coarse was originally based on almost the same imperial fractions.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] The Unified thread angle is 60° and has flattened crests (Whitworth crests are rounded).
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Thread pitch is the same in both systems except that the thread pitch for the 1⁄2 in.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] (inch) bolt is 12 threads per inch (tpi) in BSW versus 13 tpi in the UNC.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] With the advent of radiocommunication soon after its creation, the work of the ITU quickly expanded from the standardization of telegraph communications to the development of standards for telecommunications in general.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] By the end of the 19th century, differences in standards between companies were making trade increasingly difficult and strained.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] For instance, an iron and steel dealer recorded his displeasure in *The Times*: "Architects and engineers generally specify such unnecessarily diverse types of sectional material or given work that anything like economical and continuous manufacture becomes impossible.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] The Engineering Standards Committee was established in London in 1901 as the world's first national standards body.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] It subsequently extended its standardization work and became the British Engineering Standards Association in 1918, adopting the name British Standards Institution in 1931 after receiving its Royal Charter in 1929.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] The national standards were adopted universally throughout the country, and enabled the markets to act more rationally and efficiently, with an increased level of cooperation.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] After the First World War, similar national bodies were established in other countries.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] The Deutsches Institut für Normung was set up in Germany in 1917, followed by its counterparts, the American National Standard Institute and the French Commission Permanente de Standardisation, both in 1918.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Europe, the Americas, Africa, etc) or at subregional level (e.g.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Mercosur, Andean Community, South East Asia, South East Africa, etc), several Regional Standardization Organizations exist (see also Standards Organization).
[src:golden-paths/standardization] There are three regional standards organizations in Europe, which are known as European Standardization Organizations (ESOs), or European standards bodies.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] CEN, CENELEC, and ETSI are recognized via the EU's Regulation on Standardization (Regulation (EU) 1025/2012).
[src:golden-paths/standardization] CEN develops standards for numerous kinds of products, materials, services and processes.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Some sectors covered by CEN include transport equipment and services, chemicals, construction, consumer products, defence and security, energy, food and feed, health and safety, healthcare, digital sector, machinery or services.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] The European Committee for Electrotechnical Standardization (CENELEC) is the European Standardization organization developing standards in the electrotechnical area and corresponding to the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) in Europe.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] By the mid to late 19th century, efforts were being made to standardize electrical measurement.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Lord Kelvin was an important figure in this process, introducing accurate methods and apparatus for measuring electricity.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] In 1857, he introduced a series of effective instruments, including the quadrant electrometer, which cover the entire field of electrostatic measurement.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] He invented the current balance, also known as the *Kelvin balance* or *Ampere balance* (*SiC*), for the precise specification of the ampere, the standard unit of electric current.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Crompton became concerned by the large range of different standards and systems used by electrical engineering companies and scientists in the early 20th century.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Many companies had entered the market in the 1890s and all chose their own settings for voltage, frequency, current and even the symbols used on circuit diagrams.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Adjacent buildings would have totally incompatible electrical systems simply because they had been fitted out by different companies.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Crompton could see the lack of efficiency in this system and began to consider proposals for an international standard for electric engineering.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] In 1904, Crompton represented Britain at the International Electrical Congress, held in connection with Louisiana Purchase Exposition in Saint Louis as part of a delegation by the Institute of Electrical Engineers.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] He presented a paper on standardization, which was so well received that he was asked to look into the formation of a commission to oversee the process.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] By 1906 his work was complete and he drew up a permanent constitution for the International Electrotechnical Commission.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] The body held its first meeting that year in London, with representatives from 14 countries.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] In honour of his contribution to electrical standardization, Lord Kelvin was elected as the body's first President.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] The International Federation of the National Standardizing Associations (ISA) was founded in 1926 with a broader remit to enhance international cooperation for all technical standards and specifications.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] The body was suspended in 1942 during World War II.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] After the war, ISA was approached by the recently formed United Nations Standards Coordinating Committee (UNSCC) with a proposal to form a new global standards body.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] In October 1946, ISA and UNSCC delegates from 25 countries met in London and agreed to join forces to create the new International Organization for Standardization (ISO); the new organization officially began operations in February 1947.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] In general, each country or economy has a single recognized National Standards Body (NSB).
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Examples include ABNT, AENOR (now called UNE, *Spanish Association for Standardization*), AFNOR, ANSI, BSI, DGN, DIN, IRAM, JISC, KATS, SABS, SAC, SCC, SIS.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] An NSB is likely the sole member from that economy in ISO.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] NSBs may be either public or private sector organizations, or combinations of the two.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] For example, the three NSBs of Canada, Mexico and the United States are respectively the Standards Council of Canada (SCC), the General Bureau of Standards (*Dirección General de Normas*, DGN), and the American National Standards Institute (ANSI).
[src:golden-paths/standardization] SCC is a Canadian Crown Corporation, DGN is a governmental agency within the Mexican Ministry of Economy, and ANSI and AENOR are a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization with members from both the private and public sectors.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] The determinants of whether an NSB for a particular economy is a public or private sector body may include the historical and traditional roles that the private sector fills in public affairs in that economy or the development stage of that economy.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] The existence of a published standard does not necessarily imply that it is useful or correct.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Just because an item is stamped with a standard number does not, by itself, indicate that the item is fit for any particular use.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] The people who use the item or service (engineers, trade unions, etc.) or specify it (building codes, government, industry, etc.) have the responsibility to consider the available standards, specify the correct one, enforce compliance, and use the item correctly: validation and verification.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] To avoid the proliferation of industry standards, also referred to as private standards, regulators in the United States are instructed by their government offices to adopt "voluntary consensus standards" before relying upon "industry standards" or developing "government standards".
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Regulatory authorities can reference voluntary consensus standards to translate internationally accepted criteria into public policy.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] In the context of information exchange, standardization refers to the process of developing standards for specific business processes using specific formal languages.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] There are many specifications that govern the operation and interaction of devices and software on the Internet, which do not use the term "standard" in their names.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] The W3C, for example, publishes "Recommendations", and the IETF publishes "Requests for Comments" (RFCs).
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Nevertheless, these publications are often referred to as "standards", because they are the products of regular standardization processes.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Standardized product certifications such as of organic food, buildings or possibly sustainable seafood as well as standardized product safety evaluation and dis/approval procedures (e.g. regulation of chemicals, cosmetics and food safety) can protect the environment.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Moreover, standardized scientific frameworks can enable evaluation of levels of environmental protection, such as of marine protected areas, and serve as, potentially evolving, guides for improving, planning and monitoring the protection-quality, -scopes and -extents.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Such standardization is not limited to the domain of electronic devices like smartphones and phone chargers but could also be applied to e.g. the energy infrastructure.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Policy-makers could develop policies "fostering standard design and interfaces, and promoting the re-use of modules and components across plants to develop more sustainable energy infrastructure".
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Computers and the Internet are some of the tools that could be used to increase practicability and reduce suboptimal results, detrimental standards and bureaucracy, which is often associated with traditional processes and results of standardization.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Taxes and subsidies, and funding of research and development could be used complementarily.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Standardized measurement is used in monitoring, reporting and verification frameworks of environmental impacts, usually of companies, for example to prevent underreporting of greenhouse gas emissions by firms.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] In routine product testing and product analysis results can be reported using official or informal standards.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] It can be done to increase consumer protection, to ensure safety or healthiness or efficiency or performance or sustainability of products.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] It can be carried out by the manufacturer, an independent laboratory, a government agency, a magazine or others on a voluntary or commissioned/mandated basis.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Estimating the environmental impacts of food products in a standardized way – as has been done with a dataset of >57,000 food products in supermarkets – could e.g. be used to inform consumers or in policy.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] For example, such may be useful for approaches using personal carbon allowances (or similar quota) or for targeted alteration of (ultimate overall) costs.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Public information symbols (e.g. hazard symbols), especially when related to safety, are often standardized, sometimes on the international level.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Standardization is also used to ensure safe design and operation of laboratories and similar potentially dangerous workplaces, e.g. to ensure biosafety levels.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] There is research into microbiology safety standards used in clinical and research laboratories.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] In some cases, standards are being used in the design and operation of workplaces and products that can impact consumers' health.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Some of such standards seek to ensure occupational safety and health and ergonomics.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] For example, chairs (see e.g. active sitting and steps of research) could be potentially be designed and chosen using standards that may or may not be based on adequate scientific data.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] In the context of assessment, standardization may define how a measuring instrument or procedure is similar to every subjects or patients.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] For example, educational psychologist may adopt structured interview to systematically interview the people in concern.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] By delivering the same procedures, all subjects is evaluated using same criteria and minimizing any confounding variable that reduce the validity.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Some other example includes mental status examination and personality test.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] In the context of social criticism and social science, standardization often means the process of establishing standards of various kinds and improving efficiency to handle people, their interactions, cases, and so forth.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Examples include formalization of judicial procedure in court, and establishing uniform criteria for diagnosing mental disease.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Standardization in this sense is often discussed along with (or synonymously to) such large-scale social changes as modernization, bureaucratization, homogenization, and centralization of society.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] An international standard has been developed by The International Customer Service Institute.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] In the context of supply chain management and materials management, standardization covers the process of specification and use of any item the company must buy in or make, allowable substitutions, and build or buy decisions.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] The process of standardization can itself be standardized.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] There are at least four levels of standardization: compatibility, interchangeability, commonality and reference.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] These standardization processes create compatibility, similarity, measurement, and symbol standards.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Standardization has a variety of benefits and drawbacks for firms and consumers participating in the market, and on technology and innovation.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] The primary effect of standardization on firms is that the basis of competition is shifted from integrated systems to individual components within the system.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Prior to standardization a company's product must span the entire system because individual components from different competitors are incompatible, but after standardization each company can focus on providing an individual component of the system.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] When the shift toward competition based on individual components takes place, firms selling tightly integrated systems must quickly shift to a modular approach, supplying other companies with subsystems or components.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Standardization has a variety of benefits for consumers, but one of the greatest benefits is enhanced network effects.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Standards increase compatibility and interoperability between products, allowing information to be shared within a larger network and attracting more consumers to use the new technology, further enhancing network effects.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Other benefits of standardization to consumers are reduced uncertainty, because consumers can be more certain that they are not choosing the wrong product, and reduced lock-in, because the standard makes it more likely that there will be competing products in the space.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Consumers may also get the benefit of being able to mix and match components of a system to align with their specific preferences.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Once these initial benefits of standardization are realized, further benefits that accrue to consumers as a result of using the standard are driven mostly by the quality of the technologies underlying that standard.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Probably the greatest downside of standardization for consumers is lack of variety.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] There is no guarantee that the chosen standard will meet all consumers' needs or even that the standard is the best available option.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] It is also possible that a consumer will choose a product based upon a standard that fails to become dominant.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] In this case, the consumer will have spent resources on a product that is ultimately less useful to him or her as the result of the standardization process.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Much like the effect on consumers, the effect of standardization on technology and innovation is mixed.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Meanwhile, the various links between research and standardization have been identified, also as a platform of knowledge transfer and translated into policy measures (e.g.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Increased adoption of a new technology as a result of standardization is important because rival and incompatible approaches competing in the marketplace can slow or even kill the growth of the technology (a state known as market fragmentation).
[src:golden-paths/standardization] The shift to a modularized architecture as a result of standardization brings increased flexibility, rapid introduction of new products, and the ability to more closely meet individual customer's needs.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] The negative effects of standardization on technology have to do with its tendency to restrict new technology and innovation.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Standards shift competition from features to price because the features are defined by the standard.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] The degree to which this is true depends on the specificity of the standard.
[src:golden-paths/standardization] Standardization in an area also rules out alternative technologies as options while encouraging others.
[src:golden-paths/template-software-engineering] A **template processor** (also known as a **template engine** or **template parser**) is software designed to combine *template*s with data (defined by a data model) to produce resulting documents or programs.
[src:golden-paths/template-software-engineering] The language that the templates are written in is known as a **template language** or **templating language**.
[src:golden-paths/template-software-engineering] For purposes of this article, a result document is any kind of formatted output, including documents, web pages, or source code (in source code generation), either in whole or in fragments.
[src:golden-paths/template-software-engineering] A template engine is ordinarily included as a part of a web template system or application framework, and may be used also as a preprocessor or filter.
[src:golden-paths/template-software-engineering] Template engines typically include features common to most high-level programming languages, with an emphasis on features for processing plain text.
[src:golden-paths/template-software-engineering] The templating languages are generally simple substitution-only languages, in contrast to the more sophisticated facilities in full-blown template processors, but may contain some logic.
[src:golden-paths/template-software-engineering] Simple examples include ‘printf’ print format strings, found in many programming languages, and snippets, found in a number of text editors and source code editors.
[src:golden-paths/template-software-engineering] In word processors, templates are a common feature, while automatic filling in of the templates is often referred to as mail merge.
[src:golden-paths/template-software-engineering] An illustrative example of the complementary nature of parsing and templating is the `s` (substitute) command in the sed text processor, originating from search-and-replace in the ed text editor.
[src:golden-paths/template-software-engineering] For example, `s/(cat|dog)s?/\1s/g` replaces all occurrences of "cat" or "dog" with "cats" or "dogs", without duplicating an existing "s": `(cat|dog)` is the 1st (and only) sub-expression in the regexp, and `\1` in the format string substitutes this into the output.
[src:golden-paths/template-software-engineering] This may be a relational database, a source file such as XML, an alternate format of flat file database, a spreadsheet or any of other various sources of preformatted data.
[src:golden-paths/template-software-engineering] Some template processing systems are limited in the types of data that can be used.
[src:golden-paths/template-software-engineering] Others are designed for maximum flexibility and allow many different types of data.
[src:golden-paths/template-software-engineering] Additionally some template engines allow additional configuration options.
[src:golden-paths/template-software-engineering] These may consist of an entire document or a document fragment.
[src:golden-paths/template-software-engineering] Template processing is used in various contexts for different purposes.
[src:golden-paths/template-software-engineering] The specific purpose is ordinarily contingent upon the software application or template engine in use.
[src:golden-paths/template-software-engineering] However, the flexibility of template processing systems often enables unconventional uses for purposes not originally intended by the original designers.
[src:golden-paths/template-software-engineering] A **template engine** is a specific kind of template processing module that exhibits all of the major features of a modern programming language.
[src:golden-paths/template-software-engineering] The term *template engine* evolved as a generalized description of programming languages whose primary or exclusive purpose was to process templates and data to output text.
[src:golden-paths/template-software-engineering] The use of this term is most notably applied to web development using a web template system, and it is also applied to other contexts as well.
[src:golden-paths/template-software-engineering] Document generation frameworks typically use template processing as the central model for generating documents.
[src:golden-paths/template-software-engineering] A web template engine processes web templates and source data (typically from a relational database) to produce one or more output web pages or page fragments.
[src:golden-paths/template-software-engineering] It is ordinarily included as a part of a web template system or application framework.
[src:golden-paths/template-software-engineering] Currently, template processing software is most frequently used in the context of development for the web.
[src:golden-paths/template-software-engineering] XSLT is a template processing model designed by W3C.
[src:golden-paths/template-software-engineering] It is designed primarily for transformations on XML data (into web documents or other output).
[src:golden-paths/template-software-engineering] Programming languages such as Perl, Python, PHP, Ruby, C#, Java, and Go support template processing either natively, or through add-on libraries and modules.
[src:golden-paths/template-software-engineering] JavaServer Pages, Active Server Pages, Genshi (for Python), and eRuby are examples of template engines designed specifically for web application development.
[src:golden-paths/template-software-engineering] Moreover, template processing is sometimes included as a sub-feature of software packages like text editors, IDEs and relational database management systems.
